				\begin{document}$$\Sigma = \{ \mathsf{A}, \mathsf{C}, \mathsf{G}, \mathsf{U}\}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M2"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">{</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="sans-serif">A</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="sans-serif">C</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="sans-serif">G</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="sans-serif">U</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2022_4943_Article_IEq1.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. A <bold>secondary structure</bold> is a set of base-pairs <inline-formula id="IEq2"><alternatives><tex-math id="M3">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
