				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_i&lt;b_i$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M6"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2022_4943_Article_IEq3.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, and each position is involved in at most one base pair. We consider a simple, base pair based, <bold>energy model</bold> where the energy of a sequence/structure pair (<italic>w</italic>, <italic>S</italic>) is given by<disp-formula id="Equ2"><alternatives><tex-math id="M7">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
